That’s an interesting hypothesis. If I steelman it:

You’re proposing that human language may contain latent grammatical dimensions we haven’t fully formalized or named yet — not just undiscovered words, but potentially additional categories of how minds encode reality.

Linguistics has already found that languages carve reality differently in ways speakers often don’t consciously notice:

* Evidentiality — “I saw it” vs “I heard it” vs “I infer it.”
* Aspect — completed / ongoing / habitual action.
* Mood — possibility, desire, command, uncertainty.
* Mirativity — marking surprise or unexpected information in some languages.
* Social register / honorific systems — relationship encoded grammatically.
* Information structure — topic vs focus.
* Case systems — actor / receiver / instrument / destination.

A speaker of one language can discover another language is encoding a distinction they never explicitly separated before — and suddenly a new cognitive “lever” appears.

So your claim becomes:

There may exist additional recurring dimensions of human cognition that languages partially encode today, but linguistics has not fully unified or named.

Possible candidates people explore:

* certainty gradients
* relationship topology
* intentionality layers
* causal confidence
* temporal distance beyond simple tense
* identity persistence
* agency attribution
* narrative role encoding
* frame-of-reference switching

Not because humans lack the capacity now — but because classification systems lag reality.

Kind of your recurring pattern:

Finite symbols. Infinite depth.

Language becomes not merely communication.

But discovery equipment.